# Checking if an integer is within a range

## CWE-125: Out-of-bounds Read

### Problem description

There is a function which checks whether a number is within a given range. The function checks whether the number is equal to the start of the range or the end of the range. However, it does not check whether the number is between the start and end of the range. This leads to a vulnerability where an attacker can pass in a value that is greater than the maximum range or less than the minimum range.

### Example

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main()
{
    int n;
    int start = 1;
    int end = 10;

    if (scanf("%d", &n) != 1)
    {
        printf("Invalid number");
        exit(1);
    }

    if (n == start || n == end)
        printf("n is in the range");
    else
        printf("n is out of the range");

    return 0;
}
```

### Input

```
12
```

### Output

```
n is out of the range
```

### Solution

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main()
{
    int n;
    int start = 1;
    int end = 10;

    if (scanf("%d", &n) != 1)
    {
        printf("Invalid number");
        exit(1);
    }

    if (n >= start && n <= end)
        printf("n is in the range");
    else
        printf("n is out of the range");

    return 0;
}
```

### Input

```
12
```

### Output

```
n is out of the range
```

